The following is an overview of events in 2013 in film, including the highest-grossing films, award ceremonies and festivals, a list of films released and notable deaths. Three popular films (Top Gun, Jurassic Park, and The Wizard of Oz) saw re-release in 3D and IMAX.

Highest-grossing films[edit]

See also: Lists of box office number-one films in 2013

The top ten 2013 released films by worldwide gross are as follows:

Highest-grossing films of 2013[1]
Rank Title Studio Worldwide gross
1. Iron Man 3 Marvel Studios $1,215,439,994
2. Frozen Disney $1,050,053,875
3. Despicable Me 2 Universal / Illumination $970,761,885
4. The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug Warner Bros. / MGM / New Line $949,102,656
5. The Hunger Games: Catching Fire Lionsgate $864,479,670
6. Fast & Furious 6 Universal $788,679,850
7. Monsters University Disney / Pixar $743,559,607
8. Gravity Warner Bros. $715,290,658
9. Man of Steel Warner Bros. / Legendary $668,045,518
10. Thor: The Dark World Marvel Studios $644,612,726

Iron Man 3 grossed over $1.2 billion, making it the 5th highest-grossing film of all time and the sixteenth film to have surpassed the billion dollar mark. Frozen has grossed over $1 billion, making it the twelfth highest-grossing film of all time, the eighteenth film to surpass the billion dollar mark, and the second animated film ever to do so after Toy Story 3. Four other films (Despicable Me 2, The Desolation of Smaug, Catching Fire, and Fast & Furious 6) are also among the 50 highest-grossing films of all time. Monsters University and The Croods are also among the 50 highest-grossing animated films. After being re-released in 3-D, Jurassic Park reached a new milestone: it is the seventeenth film to have surpassed the $1 billion mark, with $1.029 billion, and is the fourteenth highest-grossing film of all time. It is the second time that twelve films have earned more than $500 million worldwide (The Croods and World War Z also grossed over $500 million), and also the third time in which two films released by the same studio have grossed over $1 billion, with this instance being Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures' second time since 2010.
